#Class and Inheritance
#Super is required to call the parents constructor

class ElectricCar extends Car {
  constructor(brand, model, batteryRange) {
    super(brand, model); // call parent class constructor
    this.batteryRange = batteryRange;
  }

  charge() {
    console.log(`${this.brand} ${this.model} is charging...`);
  }
}

const tesla = new ElectricCar("Tesla", "Model Y", 450);
tesla.drive(100); 
tesla.charge();

#getter and setter in JS:

Getter → a special method that lets you access a property like it’s a normal variable.

Setter → a special method that lets you control how a property is updated.

Think of them as guards for your class properties:

A getter hides how the data is calculated or stored.

A setter adds rules before changing the value.


#Getter basically makes a method to act like a normal variable where we can assign values.

class Student {
  constructor(name) {
    this.name = name;
    this._marks = 0;
  }

  // getter
  get marks() {
    return this._marks;
  }

  // setter
  set marks(value) {
    if (value < 0 || value > 100) {
      console.log("Invalid marks. Must be between 0 and 100.");
    } else {
      this._marks = value;
    }
  }
}

const s2 = new Student("Hasan");
s2.marks = 95;        // using setter
console.log(s2.marks); // 95

s2.marks = 150;       // Invalid, setter blocks it
console.log(s2.marks); // still 95
